Well when I took my history degree back in the 70's I deliberately
slanted it towards the history of Technology, especially from the 16th
to the 18th century. I did some study on China in that period and I
can't recall anything that showed a knowledge of air pressure in
enclosed spaces, whether positive or negative (vacuum).
Chinese philosophy probably predisposed thinking towards flowing or
moving things. hence good knowledge of canal building, practical wind
power, waterwheels etc. But this also led away from the idea of trapped
and enclosed spaces, a piston and cylinder for example.

Strangely enough because the Chinese must have come across the principle
of the "fire cylinder" in SE Asia, (compressing air in a bamboo tube
with a piston to heat it sufficiently to cause combustion of some tinder).
But they did nothing with the idea.
Something like Heron's turbine would have been within their concepts,
but of course it was inherently very inefficient.
Also they totally missed the idea of the pendulum, even though it was
used in geomancy in China, so western clocks were one of the most prized
exports in the 17th and 18th century.
Underlying the whole problem with China though, was of course the very
limited literacy of the artisan class.
A Chinese Newcomen or Watt would have to go through an official or
scribe just to put his ideas down on paper and thus come to the
attention of the (very conservative) Ming or Manchu officials.
The perfect example of this "ideas gap" is the fact that the Chinese
were making absolutely superb iron castings in the 13th century using
natural gas for fuel. By the 19th century their knowledge had been so
far lost that they had to use European expertise to cast cannons that
could withstand the much more powerful western gunpowder in the Opium
wars of the 1840's. Chinese made cannon were treated as a joke by the
Britsh navy after their lack of range and accuracy became clear from
experience.
Moral-Whatever your philosophy and however clever you may be, having an
ideographic written languge with more than 50,000 characters originally
based on cracked tortoise shells will hold anyone back!
Cliff Wright.
