Catch me if I'm wrong, but my reading of Needham on this does not
equate with what Pomeranz was claiming.  The basic concept behind the
steam engine was the change in pressure caused by the expansion of
water into steam, and the reverse change by its condensation back into
water.  The root of this, as I understand, were the 17th century
experiments with vacuum and atmospheric pressure. If I read Needham
correctly, none of this scientific understanding, nor any
experimentation or mechanical devices related to it, were present in
China.  However, some of the mechanisms used to harness this
principal- for example, those used for the double-acting principle and
the interconversion of rotary and rectilinear motion, appear to have
Chinese antecedents.

The closest thing I could find in Needham to a Chinese understanding
of the principles behind the steam engine is a passage from an ancient
Chinese book of magic that says that if you put boiling water in a
metal container, seal it, and toss it in a well, you will hear a loud
bang.  This certainly could have led to an understanding of
atmospheric pressure, had the author attempted to understand *why* it
happened, but it doesn't indicate that such an understanding in fact
existed.

Pomeranz's assertion that "steam engines of a sort" were found in many
societies, including China, seems so far as I can figure out be a
reference to the steam jet (basically, a heated vessel emitting a jet
of steam- for blowing up fires and stuff), which existed in the
ancient Mediterranean and central Asia- but not China, although
Needham speculates that they *may* have had it although there is no
evidence. At any rate, its not a steam engine, although it probably
inspired speculation in that direction.

I can find no evidence that the Chinese were just as likely to invent
the steam engine as England, but didn't because they didn't have the
luck of coal and industry close together like England, which is
Pomeranz's assertion. On the other hand, I find that Newcomen's
invention of the first commercially viable steam engine had roots in a
line of experimentation going back to ancient and later Renaissance
times, and given a crucial assist by 17th century science.  Thus,
England's bit of geological good luck undoubtedly helped, but some
kind of breakthrough seems to me  inevitable, while it doesn't seem
evident that Qing China was on the track to inventing it, geological
luck or no.  Anyway, that's just my take on it.

Early modern Europe seems to have been on a roll, innovationwise-
whether its technology, science, philosophy, politics...China at that
time apparently wasn't to the same degree- its previous spate of
technological innovativeness culminating in the Sung era appears to
have slowed down.  Why this was...is an interesting question.

(Some other things seem amiss with Pomeranz's argument. Although
Britain's situation was obviously conducive to the use of Newcomen's
steam engine, it also rapidly became used in continental Europe, ie.
France, Germany, Austria, Hungary and Sweden. And its not like China
didn't have coal although it didn't require draining like English
mines.  He notes that most coal were far from the economic centers of
the country, but then mentions some that was near the Grand Canal, but
that was inefficiently utilized because the government officials
arranged for it to be exploited by small-scale, ineffective mining
operations. Hrm...)
