I got my information from Temple's abridgement of Needham, in which he
says the sixth century Old Manual of Metalurgical Water-Power
Technology by Kao Lung Chih stated that a "reverse" of the steam
engine involved a water wheel driving the pistons to produce a steady
and strong blast of air for metal-working furnances. The operation was
double-acting, ie compressing air in both parts of the stroke. Instead
of an "input" of steam compressed the "output" is air compressed.

The article is reproduced at http://archiver.rootsweb.com/th/read/GEN-
MEDIEVAL/2004-01/1074293260
