I saw a bit on the History Channel last night about cars, the long
history of personal vehicles. One character sort of stood out,
Ferdinand Verbiest, a Flemish Jesuit who corrected the Chinese
calendar, attained the status of head of the Imperial Mathematical
Board, invented a steam engine for ships and is reputed to have made
either a trolley, thereby anticipating the railroad, or a steam car.
All in the mid-17th century.

