Yeah, I read about the same thing in Needham. Basically, as I've said,
the Chinese device anticipated the double-acting principle and the
transformation of reciprocating into rotative motion, which were
useful concept for fully utilizing steam power although the earliest
steam engines didn't have them. However, the Chinese lacked the
concept of utilizing the vacuum and the change in volume caused by the
transformation of water from liquid to gas and back, which was of
course the crux of the matter.  To say they were close to the steam
engine would be a little like saying that because someone had metal
tubes mounted on tripods with alt-azimuth gears, but didn't have
lenses, they were close to inventing the telescope.

I looked at Temple's book some time ago, and my impression was that it
had a polemical edge to it and ought to be read with caution. At least
that was my impression, although admittedly I did just skim through it
a couple years ago. Needham had, as he admitted, a tendency to take
his admittedly impressive facts and stretch them as far as possible
interpretation-wise, but Temple seems to have taken this to a whole
other level. Hence misleading statements such as "The essential design
of the steam engine, lacking only the crank-shaft, was invented in
China before the steam engine existed".

Perhaps Pomeranz read Temple and then, to look better, cited Needham
without really reading the original work carefully.

Maybe this is a cheap shot, but the fact that Temple (I'm not making
this up) wrote a book about human civilization being jump-started by
fish aliens, strikes me as a bad sign.  I find it baffling that the
popularization of Needham was left up to such a fellow.
